The presence of IEEE in Europe is assured by, on the one hand, the IEEE individual members (nearly 60,000 engineers, scientists and technical professionals who comprise IEEE's European membership), and on the other hand the IEEE European Public Policy Committee (EPPC).&#xd;
&#xd;
The EPPC’s structure consists of the following bodies:&#xd;
&#xd;
The EPPC is a IEEE Committee with a Chair and Committee members, responsible to the IEEE Board of Directors for the coordination of public policy activities relevant to the interests of IEEE members in European Union (EU) and European Free Trade Association (EFTA) countries, which are designed to benefit IEEE members, engineering professionals and the general public.&#xd;
The EPPC also convenes two working groups, one on Information and Communication Technologies (ICT) and one on Energy. Both groups are composed of a Chair and IEEE volunteers from the EU and EFTA countries, with expertise in these technical fields.
